name: Imo Pocha
review: A cozy korean spot with limited seating, authentic menu, and soju and beer towers. Super busy on the weekends and pretty chill to pop-in during the weekdays. No reservation system at the time of this review. Prices are normal for Seattle standards, but portion sizes are a bit on the smaller end. Snuggly fit my group of 6.

name: Seoul Tofu & Jjim
review: A newer Korean establishment that serves tofu and meat badsed Korean dishes. It is the main Korean restaurant on Broadway of Cap Hill. Very spacious seating and never much of a wait to get a table, even during peak hours. The Bibimbap is amazing here, as well as their tofu dishes. They also give you 5 free side dishes that are refillable. And most times, they offer a free dessert (ice cream) at the end of the meal. Most of their menu items are pricey, but good food nontheless.

name: Pho Than Brothers
review: A local chain serving beef, chicken & vegetarian pho. Prices are great for what you get, and I've never had a bad bowl of pho here. The pho is served super quickly. The interior is quite basic, but functional. Not much else to say - a dependable place for a good bowl of pho.

name: Rondo Japanese Kitchen
review: A more chic spot for Japanese foods, including izakaya-style snacks, donburi bowls, and Japanese cocktails. The presentation of the foods are beautiful and the food comes out relatively quick. May need a rservation at peak hours. This is a more expensive option, as you'll most likely purchase multiple options due to food sizes and their other menu options.

name: Fog√≥n Cocina Mexicana
review: A vibrant, informal, family-owned Mexican cantina with homemade corn tortillas & tequila cocktails. The happy hour menu here is fantastic, like unbeleivable. The staff are always kind and the food is consistently good.

name: Pelicana Chicken
review: A famous asian chain landing in Seattle with a variety of comfort Korean fried dishes - most known for their fried chicken. They have a variety of options for the kind of fried chicken as well as the type of sauce that chicken is drenched in. The interior gives a more bar vibe. The portion sizes are good, but the prices are way more than you would expect. I'd reccomend eating here with a group.

name: Biang Biang Noodles
review: An industrial-style Chinese noodle house serving biang biang style noodles, dumplings, baos, and chicken wings. The noodles are hand pulled and you can even see the staff in the back whip them around before making your dish. So chewy and so delicious! Their drinks are decent, but you can get milk tea elsewhere.
address: 601 E Pike St Unit 100, Seattle, WA 98122

name: Ayutthaya
review: A cozy spot specializing in Thai classics such as coconut chicken and drunken noodles, with a decent happy hour. Interior is very homey with lots of wood furniture. There was 1 person front of house and they were super kind and had such great multitasking skills. Food is good, but nothing to rave about. Will definitely satisfy your thai cravings.

name: Kati Vegan Thai
review: A thai restaurant that servers an entirely vegan menu with cocktails in a petitie, modern space. Located in South Lake Union, this restaurant is a breath of fresh air. Has indoor and outdoor seating and I've never had to get a reservation here. More expensive than other thai resturants in the area, but food is consistently good. Highly reccomend their cauliflower appetizer.

name: Vinason Pho Kitchen
review: A very small Vietnamese corner cafe serving pho, banh mi, and vermicelli. Quite expensive for what you're getting. You order via a screen and you pick up from a counter. Sometimes, the wait can be long. This is a small restaurant and there is only bar seating at the windows. Other than that, you need to eat it elsewhere.
